  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Gift for Jungjeol
  author: Kim Maengseong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Counting on my fingers, it has been the year of Imsin—
    over ten years now since we first became friends.
    We shot at clay pigeons in the temple groves,
    raced our horses through the ruins of Yuljeong.

    Exiled to this distant place, who would have known me?
    Yet you, rising to join my song,
    lifted my spirit high.

    A single cup of wine already speaks of bonds so deep—
    how much more so when shared with fine fish and good company?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Imsin year (임신년) refers to a specific year in the traditional East Asian sexagenary cycle, likely 1572 CE in the Joseon context.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to shooting and horsing through sacred and abandoned places suggest youthful adventures and carefree times the friends shared together.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs a traditional motif of wine and food as expressions of deep friendship and mutual respect in East Asian poetic tradition.
